sely. This might happen if the test source context isn’t current. JaCoCo could have issues with private or synthetic methods in the report, impacting coverage claims. Workflow expects tests for these unknown cases, but I'm not sure how to improve this without modifying the original library source. Perhaps using a subclass could work, but dynamic reports from static analysis might still show \\\"Unknown Source.\\\"\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Refining JaCoCo mapping**\\n\\nI'm considering whether JaCoCo can still map via probes. Maybe it requires branch coverage rather than just method coverage, but I can't fix that right now. The user is asking for refinement. Perhaps previous serialization connected to library hooks, but dynamic call sites might not work since arguments are byte arrays that don't provide metadata. To generate Native Image metadata for BCDSTU, I could try using `ObjectOutputStream.writeObject(privateKey)` from a top-level caller test, but that didn't work. Directly calling `writeObject` or `readObject` with MethodHandles and a custom `ObjectOutputStream` could be worth exploring, yet JaCoCo shows coverage already.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating coverage issues**\\n\\nI’m considering whether the dynamic coverage might be false because the callsite wasn't reached. Jacoco indicates that it's reached after natural, so changing method handles won't affect method coverage. Unless the specific callsite isn’t fully covered? Jacoco is method-level only, but the dynamic tool might track instructions more precisely. The method has seven instructions, and all should be covered. I'm wondering if the dynamic report was generated before the test compile since the timestamps reflect afterward.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Inspecting Jacoco exec**\\n\\nI’m thinking about whether to use the Jacoco exec file before running the new test. The Jacoco XML output includes the test, but there’s something odd about the dynamic report being false. I want to take a closer look at the dynamic report generation script to understand why it’s showing “Unknown Source.” This could be crucial to figuring out any potential issues before moving forward. Let’s dive into that script!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_hxmja54T8GhGVF4ao9OO0tkN|fc_048c618117f648020169fbc79e44c0819780e917cb26b3c122", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg \"dynamic-access-coverage|covered\" build.gradle forge -n | head -100"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 534, "output": 1102, "cacheRead": 34304, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 35940, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778108291802, "responseId": "resp_048c618117f648020169fbc784941c8197b4eed6410f275967"}}
